A dual description of decoherence  After a bubble nucleates, it begins to expand. The standard way
to follow the subsequent 
evolution of the bubble is to switch from the static
coordinates () to some global, e.g., conformal, coordinates. 
In such global
coordinates, decoherence between the states built near the minima
of the potential-we now refer to these states as  and 
-can be attributed to super-Hubble modes of the field
. On the other hand, in the dual description, decoherence
is attributed to interaction of sub-Hubble modes with an "environment" 
located inside the observer's horizon, so
it will be sufficient for our purposes to work
with a single Hubble patch described by the metric ().
