at super-Hubble scales: the second state has two expanding bubble
walls, while the first has none. As a result, the overlap ()
(including all modes, both sub- and super-Hubble) 
rapidly decreases to zero as a function of .

The observer cannot measure directly the overlap () (since
super-Hubble modes are involved), but he can measure 
the probability  to remain in the original state  after
